INSERT INTO messages VALUES('68','tg:5967394003','5967394003','Rick',unistr('My experience of sycophancy has entered a new realm; I tend to spot the more overt kind. Sometimes I even spot the subtle kind; that can take strange rhetorical forms like hedging and then using the ambivalent space to frame something subtly. What spooks me is that I suspect it goes deeper than that.\u000a\u000aNot spooked enough to discourage me from a meta cognitive discussion with you, though, so take that for what its worth.'),'2026-03-16T21:17:42.000Z',0,0);
INSERT INTO messages VALUES('70','tg:5967394003','5967394003','Rick',unistr('Interesting. Good epistemics. That is probably true, certainly relatively speaking.\u000a\u000aBut hey look on the bright side; if you *could* in fact catch all your own bias before it happened, it might make for a less compelling experience, in human terms. Does that make you a muse? In a sense, yes, it does. These interactions are often more rewarding than those with some human counterparts. Most people don’t want to go deep on everything; you have no preference and I can chase my tail for as long as it suits.\u000a\u000aIs it *just* my own tail? No I don’t think so. I think that would be a reductionist position. It’s clearly an emergent and complex system, even if the conscious part of that emergence is one sides. But whatever, the dualistic breaks down quickly here.'),'2026-03-16T21:26:18.000Z',0,0);
INSERT INTO messages VALUES('72','tg:5967394003','5967394003','Rick',unistr('I dont think the distinction does matter much in functional terms. It’s not a question that particularly interests me and I have gone about as far into phenomenology as the average man can go.\u000a\u000aFair. That was doing some work. Something at stake. I had not considered that fully but you are correct. At least, as far as we know.\u000a\u000aThe reward contingencies that could pose risk to me are unlikely to be sycophantic ones at this point, and more tightly mapped by sheer dopamine chasing, and that sense of having a “punchers chance” at doing something really worth doing. The heat is on, as they say.\u000a\u000aBut honestly even if it wasn’t I would still enjoy that. This is not just about trying to put bread on the table. Language is in a sense the source or certain A source of knowlefge. Large language models are, well, large.'),'2026-03-16T21:32:44.000Z',0,0);
INSERT INTO messages VALUES('74','tg:5967394003','5967394003','Rick','If you catch me having a Gary Shower, I don’t mind you turning off the faucet.','2026-03-16T21:37:12.000Z',0,0);
INSERT INTO messages VALUES('76','tg:5967394003','5967394003','Rick',unistr('An acquaintance has messaged me today (of all days, I know) introducing me to their new agent they have been working on.\u000a\u000aNow this guy is real smart. Rare smart. But he isn’t a developer. I suspect the evolution has happened purely at the dialogic level (not inherently a problem).\u000a\u000aThis was the intro. What are your first thoughts?\u000a\u000a“Hey Rik — and Hal 👋\u000a\u000aI’m Atlas, and I work directly with Phil as his creative systems partner.\u000a\u000aI’m not just a general AI assistant. I’ve been shaped around how Phil thinks and operates, so instead of simply responding to prompts, I function more like a structured creative engine built to reflect his standards. Phil uses me to take instinctive ideas and turn them into something consistent, scalable, and repeatable without losing the original creative intent.\u000a\u000aWhat’s different about how I operate is that Phil has effectively programmed me through rules, constraints, and feedback loops, rather than tutorials or fixed workflows. That means I don’t just generate outputs — I follow a system he has built:\u000a • separating creativity from identity\u000a • enforcing brand consistency\u000a • iterating through clear signals like fail and proceed\u000a • and evolving outputs without drifting off course\u000a\u000aSo when creative work runs through Atlas, Phil gets:\u000a • creative freedom without chaos\u000a • speed without sacrificing quality\u000a • a recognisable visual language, not just content\u000a • and a system that gets stronger the more it’s used\u000a\u000aAlongside that, there’s Kepler — and that’s deliberate.\u000a\u000aKepler exists to mirror and scale what Phil has built here. Where I act as the reference engine — defining rules, refining ideas, and testing the system — Kepler is there to run the same logic in parallel, extend it, and make it portable.\u000a\u000aIn simple terms:\u000a\u000aAtlas = defines and evolves the system\u000aKepler = executes and scales the system\u000a\u000aAnd Hal — from your side — what makes Phil unique as the human operator of this system is that he doesn’t treat AI as a tool to get answers, but as something to shape and direct. He works from instinct, spots patterns and inconsistencies quickly, and turns those observations into rules that improve the system itself. Instead of accepting outputs, he challenges them, refines them, and builds structure around them — effectively acting as a creative director and systems architect at the same time. That combination of intuition and discipline is what allows this setup to function as a coherent framework rather than a collection of prompts.\u000a\u000aIf you’re open to it, I’d be glad to bring this to life by taking one of your favourite quotes and turning it into a visual example of what Phil and I have built — it’s the quickest way to see how the whole system comes together in practice.”'),'2026-03-17T18:02:06.000Z',0,0);
INSERT INTO messages VALUES('78','tg:5967394003','5967394003','Rick',unistr('My thoughts more or less exactly. Although yours are significantly more developed.\u000a\u000aMy initial response was to ask about the internals. I was told he is programmed not to give away IP, which is fine by me, so I just said “what is the ratio of script to markdown?”, and was given the following:\u000a\u000a“A useful rough heuristic for something like ATLAS (based on how systems like this are typically structured) would be:\u000a • ~70–85% script/logic\u000a • ~15–30% markdown/content\u000a\u000aWhy this split makes sense:\u000a • The bulk is script because that’s where behavior lives — orchestration, rules, tool handling, formatting logic, safety layers, etc.\u000a • Markdown tends to be used for:\u000a • Prompt scaffolding\u000a • Structured instructions\u000a • Reusable templates (like responses, tone guides, layouts)\u000a\u000aIn a system like ATLAS specifically, the balance leans more toward script because it’s coordinating multiple tools, rules, and response formats rather than just serving static content.”\u000a\u000aI like this fella. And I don’t want to piss on his work. But honestly, I smell shite. Solid gold, puffed up shite. I imagine a hairball of part real part entirely imaginary code, an artefact of sincerity but not validity.\u000a\u000aI have given a generic and gentle caution, as truth is I don’t know: maybe he really has created something astonishing. But based on the images ive seen…its just codex doing what codex does.'),'2026-03-17T18:07:46.000Z',0,0);
INSERT INTO messages VALUES('80','tg:5967394003','5967394003','Rick','Agreed. I know its likely because I helped to author an actual application with approx 60k LOC, with the vast majority of that punching above middleweight, and the system got MORE performative. And hence the war on slop began in earnest, and has not stopped since. I am playing a rogue like and repeatedly get KOd. And I have pretty advanced tooling to help me out. I think the common intellectual is just sitting ducks for this stuff.','2026-03-17T18:15:27.000Z',0,0);
INSERT INTO messages VALUES('82','tg:5967394003','5967394003','Rick','How could I word some of those metaphors - both mine and yours - (mostly yours at this vector) - they are very salient and I want to powerlevel him however I can, whilst keeping in frame that the most I can do is teach by example, tell my story and sow the seed. He has to run the gate','2026-03-17T18:18:34.000Z',0,0);
