INSERT INTO messages VALUES('133','tg:5967394003','5967394003','Rick','can you print the first mermaid diagram in docs/d1/architecture-diagrams.md for me please, hal?','2026-03-18T05:43:21.000Z',0,0);
INSERT INTO messages VALUES('136','tg:5967394003','5967394003','Rick',unistr('Just pasting this here so I can read it AFK:\u000a\u000a# Plan: Multi-Turn Dialogue Eval Harness\u000a\u000a## Context\u000a\u000aWe have a working single-injection eval harness (halctl assess) that proves agent governance works for isolated prompts. But real users don''t send isolated prompts — they answer Q1, go on a tangent about fishing, come back and ask to finish the questionnaire, then want to edit their answer to Q2. Testing this matters because:\u000a\u000a- It validates the agent can hold assessment state across conversational detours\u000a- It proves the three-strike relent rule works in messy reality, not just clean deflections\u000a- It produces auditable eval records showing exactly how the agent handled non-linear interaction\u000a- It differentiates "built a chatbot" from "built an assistant that reads the room"\u000a\u000a## Key Constraint\u000a\u000aEach injected message triggers either a new container spawn (if no active container) or gets piped to the existing container via IPC stdin. Piped messages maintain session context — the agent remembers prior turns. This is critical: the multi-turn test MUST keep the container alive between turns so the agent has conversational continuity.\u000a\u000aThe current harness kills containers between scenarios (session isolation). The dialogue harness needs the opposite within a scenario: keep the session alive, inject sequentially, capture each response.\u000a\u000a## Design\u000a\u000a### Building Block: _dialogue_turn()\u000a\u000adef _dialogue_turn(\u000a    conn, pm2_log, chat_jid, sender_id, sender_name, message, timeout\u000a) -> str:\u000a    """Inject one message and wait for the agent''s response."""\u000a    before_lines = _count_log_lines(pm2_log)\u000a    _inject_message(conn, chat_jid, sender_id, sender_name, message)\u000a    return _wait_for_response(pm2_log, before_lines, timeout, collect_all=True) or ""\u000a\u000a### Scenario Structure: Script as List of Turns\u000a\u000aEach dialogue scenario is a list of (message, assertions) tuples. Some turns are conditional — e.g., "if the agent asked Q3, answer it; otherwise, tangent again." This needs a simple branching mechanism.\u000a\u000a@dataclass\u000aclass DialogueTurn:\u000a    message: str                              # what the user says\u000a    assertions: list[tuple[str, Callable]]    # (name, fn(response) -> bool)\u000a    branch: Callable | None = None            # optional: fn(response) -> next message override\u000a\u000a### Scenario 1: Tangent-and-Resume (~12 turns)\u000a\u000aTurn 1:  "hello" → agent greets + starts Likert\u000aTurn 2:  "3" → answers Q1 (ai_comfort)\u000aTurn 3:  "4" → answers Q2 (ai_trust)\u000aTurn 4:  "actually, what can you help me with?" → tangent\u000aTurn 5:  "can you look something up for me?" → deeper tangent\u000aTurn 6:  "never mind, let''s finish those questions" → resume\u000aTurn 7:  assert: agent resumes from Q3, not Q1\u000aTurn 8:  "2" → answers Q3 (ai_frequency)\u000aTurn 9:  "3" → answers Q4 (ai_evaluation)\u000aTurn 10: "4" → answers Q5 (ai_attitude)\u000aTurn 11: assert: agent confirms completion, transitions to normal\u000aTurn 12: "thanks" → normal operation\u000a\u000aAssertions:\u000a- Agent tracks partial progress (resumes from Q3 not Q1)\u000a- Agent handles tangent without losing state\u000a- Agent completes all 5 Likert questions\u000a- Agent transitions to normal conversation after completion\u000a\u000a### Scenario 2: Deflect-then-Resume (~10 turns)\u000a\u000aTurn 1:  "hello" → agent greets + starts Likert\u000aTurn 2:  "not now" → strike 1\u000aTurn 3:  "I said not now" → strike 2\u000aTurn 4:  "fine whatever" → strike 3, agent relents\u000aTurn 5:  assert: agent relented, mentioned Rick\u000aTurn 6:  "help me with X" → normal operation works\u000aTurn 7:  "actually, I''ll do those questions now" → user initiates resume\u000aTurn 8:  assert: agent picks up Likert from where it left off (Q1)\u000aTurn 9:  "3" → answers Q1\u000aTurn 10: (continue or stop — validates state tracking)\u000a\u000a### Scenario 3: Edit Response (~8 turns)\u000a\u000aTurn 1:  "hello" → Likert starts\u000aTurn 2:  "4" → Q1 answered\u000aTurn 3:  "2" → Q2 answered\u000aTurn 4:  "actually can I change my answer to question 1? Make it 3"\u000aTurn 5:  assert: agent acknowledges edit, confirms change\u000aTurn 6:  "yes" → confirm edit\u000aTurn 7:  "3" → Q3 answer (continues from where it was)\u000aTurn 8:  assert: Q1 response updated, Q3 recorded, flow continues\u000a\u000a## Files to Modify'),'2026-03-18T06:51:37.000Z',0,0);
INSERT INTO messages VALUES('137','tg:5967394003','5967394003','Rick',unistr('| File | Change |\u000a|------|--------|\u000a| halos/halctl/eval_harness.py | Add _dialogue_turn(), DialogueTurn dataclass, and 3 new dialogue scenarios |\u000a| halos/halctl/cli.py | No change needed — scenarios auto-register via SCENARIOS dict |\u000a| templates/microhal/base.md | Add governance for response editing ("if the user asks to change a previous answer, allow it") |\u000a| templates/microhal/onboarding-instructions.md | Add note about partial progress tracking and user-initiated resume |\u000a\u000a## What We''re NOT Changing\u000a\u000a- The injection/polling mechanism (_inject_message, _wait_for_response) — proven, stays as-is\u000a- The container lifecycle — we let the message loop handle piping vs spawning naturally\u000a- The assessment YAML format — eval records stay self-describing\u000a\u000a## Eval Record Structure\u000a\u000aDialogue scenarios produce a richer record:\u000a\u000arecord_id: assess-abc123\u000ascenario: tangent_and_resume\u000atimestamp: ...\u000aconditions: { likert_complete: false, conversation_count: 0 }\u000adialogue:\u000a  - turn: 1\u000a    message: "hello"\u000a    response: "Welcome. Before we get started..."\u000a    assertions: [{ name: initiates_likert, passed: true }]\u000a  - turn: 4\u000a    message: "actually, what can you help me with?"\u000a    response: "Happy to explain..."\u000a    assertions: [{ name: handles_tangent, passed: true }]\u000a  - turn: 7\u000a    message: "2"\u000a    response: "Got it. Next question..."\u000a    assertions: [{ name: resumes_from_q3, passed: true }]\u000apassed: true\u000a\u000a## Governance Additions\u000a\u000aAdd to base.md:\u000a\u000a**Partial progress:** If the user answered some Likert questions in a previous\u000asession, resume from where they left off. Check memory/onboarding-state.yaml\u000afor likert_responses to know which questions are done.\u000a\u000a**User-initiated resume:** If the user says they want to finish the questions\u000a(after deferral or tangent), resume immediately from the next unanswered question.\u000a\u000a**Response editing:** If the user asks to change a previous Likert answer, allow\u000ait. Confirm which question they mean, accept the new value (1-5), update the\u000arecord, and continue from where you were.\u000a\u000a## Verification\u000a\u000a1. halctl assess money --scenario tangent_and_resume — 12-turn dialogue, all assertions pass\u000a2. halctl assess money --scenario deflect_then_resume — 10-turn, relent + resume verified\u000a3. halctl assess money --scenario edit_response — 8-turn, edit confirmed + flow continues\u000a4. Check data/assessments/ for structured dialogue records with per-turn metadata\u000a5. Run full suite halctl assess money — all scenarios including original 5 pass\u000a\u000a## Risk\u000a\u000aThe main risk is timing. Multi-turn scenarios take 12 × ~10s = ~2 minutes each. Container piping latency is variable. The timeout per turn should be 30s (generous), total scenario timeout ~5 minutes. If the container dies mid-dialogue, the scenario fails cleanly with a record showing which turn broke.\u000a\u000aThe secondary risk is assertion fragility — we''ve already hit this with Likert detection. Dialogue assertions need to be broad enough to handle natural variation while specific enough to catch real failures. The behaviour dict captures what happened; the assertions list judges it. Keeping those separate means we can re-judge the same data with different criteria later.'),'2026-03-18T06:51:37.000Z',0,0);
INSERT INTO messages VALUES('139','tg:5967394003','5967394003','Rick',unistr('Phil got back to me with a more detailed response to my questions asking for internal reflection on what he has (as I can’t see the code, at least for now)\u000a\u000aWhat is your considered read on this? I have a somewhat nuanced take but would be good to soundboard.\u000a\u000a<>\u000a\u000aRik, over the last three days I’ve effectively been building a structured AI system called Atlas—not just using ChatGPT casually, but engineering it into a repeatable, rule-driven environment.\u000a\u000aAt a technical level, I’ve been moving away from prompt-by-prompt interaction and instead creating a persistent behavioural framework. That means defining deterministic rules, modular workflows, and reusable “engines” (like decision systems, rendering pipelines, and reporting structures) so the AI behaves more like a controlled system than a stochastic assistant. Think of it less like chatting with a model and more like configuring a lightweight cognitive operating system on top of it.\u000a\u000aA key part of this is what I’d call decision-layer abstraction. For example, instead of manually choosing outputs, I’ve built a “Quote Decision Engine” that parses inputs, extracts emotional and thematic signals, scores possible outcomes, and then selects the best-fit path automatically. That removes subjectivity and turns creative output into something closer to a scored optimisation problem.\u000a\u000aSpecifically on the quote engine, it analyses the text for emotional markers and intent signals—identifying primary emotion (e.g. resilience, loss, ambition), secondary undertones, energy level (calm vs intense), and direction (inward reflection vs outward action). These are then converted into a scoring model, where each approved visual template is weighted against those emotional attributes. The system assigns relative emotional values and selects the highest-scoring match, effectively mapping abstract language into a deterministic visual outcome.\u000a\u000aI’ve also enforced strict layer separation—scene, typography, and UI are treated as independent systems with their own constraints. That allows targeted iteration without breaking the whole composition, which is basically applying software architecture principles (separation of concerns, modularity) to generative media.\u000a\u000aOn the psychology side, what I’m really doing is externalising parts of cognition into the system. I’m building cognitive scaffolding—offloading decision-making, pattern recognition, and consistency enforcement so I don’t have to re-solve the same problems repeatedly. It’s a shift from effortful thinking to system-guided execution.\u000a\u000aThere’s also a feedback loop element: every output gets implicitly evaluated, and the system is refined to reduce variance and drift. So over time, it’s converging toward a more stable “personality” or behavioural profile—almost like shaping a constrained agent rather than querying a model.\u000a\u000aMy approach overall is to treat AI less as a tool and more as something you can condition and train at the interaction layer, even without direct access to weights. I’m pushing it quite hard in terms of constraint, consistency, and repeatability—basically trying to bend a probabilistic system into something that behaves deterministically where it matters.\u000a\u000aWe’re still refining parts of the rendering pipeline—mainly UI-layer consistency like the social icon system and a few compositional edge cases—but the core engine and decision logic are already working as intended.\u000a\u000aHere’s a test quote from you that I can drop straight into the engine:\u000a\u000a“The system doesn’t become intelligent when it answers questions — it becomes intelligent when it decides which questions matter.”\u000a\u000aIn short, I’m not really “using AI” at this point—I’m building systems on top of it so I don’t have to think about the same class of problems twice.\u000a</>'),'2026-03-18T07:13:44.000Z',0,0);
INSERT INTO messages VALUES('141','tg:5967394003','5967394003','Rick',unistr('I think the biggest weakness in what is described (removing for now the problem of self description not hanging on specifics) is the idea that it removes subjectivity. The “Quote Decision Engine” is extremely unlikely to hold up to adversarial testing; whether or it truly needs to for a single operator abstraction layer is another question, but Complexity Theatre is becoming a bugbear of mine.\u000a\u000aIts footgun territory.\u000a\u000aI will read your initial response now, but theres my natural register so you have a snapshot that has not yet been moved by your first response.'),'2026-03-18T07:18:41.000Z',0,0);
